341. Am Surg. 1979 Nov;45(11):684-99.

Aortic valve replacement and the senior citizen.

Jones TW, Thomas GI, Stavney LS, Manhas DR.

The elderly patient, regardless of age, faces an early demise from progressive 
cardiac decompensation secondary to aortic valve disease. Aortic valve 
replacement can be carried out at a reasonable operative risk and extend the 
longevity to very close to that of normal life expectancy. It is our feeling, 
based on these results, that patients with significant symptoms secondary to 
aortic valvular disease, regardless of age and without other major organ 
problems, should be given the choice of aortic valve replacement to enhance the 
quality and quantity of their lives.

